  "prompt": "What are some cool Java tricks?",
  "response": "Java is a versatile language with many interesting features and tricks that can improve your coding efficiency and make your code cleaner. Here are some cool Java tricks:\n\n1. **Using `var` for Local Variable Type Inference** (Java 10+):\n   Instead of specifying the type of a local variable explicitly, you can use `var` to let the compiler infer the type.\n   ```java\n   var list = new ArrayList<String>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Enhanced Switch Statements** (Java 12+):\n   Java 12 introduced a new form of the switch statement that allows you to use arrow syntax and return values.\n   ```java\n   String result = switch (day) {\n       case MONDAY -> \"Start of the week\";\n       case FRIDAY -> \"End of the work week\";\n       case SATURDAY, SUNDAY -> \"Weekend!\";\n       default -> \"Midweek day\";\n   };\n   ```\n\n3. **Text Blocks** (Java 13+):\n   You can use text blocks to create multi-line strings without the hassle of escape sequences.\n   ```java\n   String json = \"\"\"\n       {\n           \"name\": \"John\",\n           \"age\": 30\n       }\n   \"\"\";\n   ```\n\n4. **Optional Class**:\n   Use the `Optional` class to avoid null checks and to represent optional values.\n   ```java\n   Optional<String> optionalName = Optional.ofNullable(getName());\n   optionalName.ifPresent(name -> System.out.println(name));\n   ```\n\n5. **Streams and Lambdas**:\n   Java Streams allow you to process collections in a functional style. You can use lambdas to make your code concise.\n   ```java\n   List<String> names = Arrays.asList(\"Alice\", \"Bob\", \"Charlie\");\n   names.stream()\n        .filter(name -> name.startsWith(\"A\"))\n        .forEach(System.out::println);\n   ```\n\n6. **Method References**:\n   Instead of using lambda expressions, you can use method references for cleaner code.\n   ```java\n   names.forEach(System.out::println);\n   ```\n\n7. **Default Methods in Interfaces**:\n   You can provide default implementations in interfaces, allowing you to add new methods without breaking existing implementations.\n   ```java\n   interface MyInterface {\n       default void myDefaultMethod() {\n           System.out.println(\"Default implementation\");\n       }\n   }\n   ```\n\n8. **Static Imports**:\n   You can use static imports to avoid repetitively referencing the class name.\n   ```java\n   import static java.lang.Math.*;\n   double area = PI * pow(radius, 2);\n   ```\n\n9. **Annotations**:\n   Create custom annotations to add metadata to your code. Use reflection to access annotations at runtime.\n   ```java\n   @Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)\n   @Target(ElementType.METHOD)\n   public @interface MyCustomAnnotation {\n       String value();\n   }\n   ```\n\n10. **Immutable Collections** (Java 9+):\n    You can create immutable lists, sets, and maps easily.\n    ```java\n    List<String> immutableList = List.of(\"A\", \"B\", \"C\");\n    Set<String> immutableSet = Set.of(\"A\", \"B\", \"C\");\n    Map<String, String> immutableMap = Map.of(\"key1\", \"value1\", \"key2\", \"value2\");\n    ```\n\n11. **Using `CompletableFuture`** for Asynchronous Programming:\n    Handle asynchronous tasks more easily with `CompletableFuture`.\n    ```java\n    CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {\n        // Some background task\n        return \"Result\";\n    }).thenAccept(result -> System.out.println(result));\n    ```\n\n12. **Pattern Matching for `instanceof`** (Java 16+):\n    Simplify type checks and casting using pattern matching.\n    ```java\n    if (obj instanceof String str) {\n        System.out.println(str.toUpperCase());\n    }\n    ```\n\nThese tricks can help enhance your Java programming skills and make your code more efficient and readable.",
